defaultHow defaultresilient are the UK’s transport networks (including road, rail and air) to adverse winter weather?default&#xa0;
default2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultM.A.G airports have taken steps to ensure that, as far as possible, flights can continue operating safely during periods of snowfall. 
defaultAll M.A.G
default airports ha
defaultve a comprehensive Winter Operations Plan, 
defaultwhich comes into effect on 1 November 
defaultfollowing consultation with airfield tenants. The plan explains what preparations have been made to deal with extreme winter weather, and sets out roles and responsibilities.
default 
defaultIt also 
defaultincludes a detailed set of crisis management plans in the event of severe disruption
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultStansted Airport’s plan is subject to rigorous testing programmes, including summer desktop exercise run jointly with airlines, handling agents and operational t
defaulteams. A Terminal Welfare Plan, also operated in conjunction with airlines, sets out roles and responsibilities for passenger information, provisions, facilities and hotels and rebooking.
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Winter Operations Plan is reviewed annually and
default improvements added based on lessons learned
default. 
defaultFor example, 
defaultthe Terminal team at Manchester have carried out additional work this year to make the passenger welfare element more robust. This included working with procurement colleagues to look at how to sec
defaulture additional supplies at short notice; working with Manchester City Council to pool resources; reviewing communications, such as use of passenger information screens; and working closely with retail colleagues to ensure the availability of food, drink an
defaultd essentials.
default 
defaultOur terminal and operations teams also draw on best practice from other European airports.
default&#xa0;
default2.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWork is 
defaultalso 
defaultunderway at Manchester to explore how to ensure the safety and well-being of colleagues, but looking at how they can get into work, e.g. 
defaultadvance booking of hotels for operation critical colleagues and call out groups for those living close by.
defaultWhat lessons have been learned since the severe weather experienced in the winter of 2009-10? What practical changes have been made to ensure the UK defaultis now better equipped to deal with severe weather?default2.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultM.A.G airports have invested substantially in snow clearing equipment since the severe 2009-10 winter (see below for details). Lessons learned included increased supplies of and storage areas for road sal
defaultt and de-icer; improvements to crisis management systems and changes to weather forecasting information, to allow for more accurate forecasting.
default 
default&#xa0;
default2.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDespite extensive preparation and investment
default, constant snowfall remains a significant challenge. Just 3mm of snow on the ground sees airfield operations slow down and constant snowfall makes any clearing operation 
defaultprolonged and challenging
default.
default Manchester Airport has invested in equipment to monitor the
default ground temperature (snow will melt if the ground is warmer than freezing) which means that 
defaultappropriate airfield anti
default-icing 
defaultaction
default can be 
defaultundertaken
default 
defaultin a timely and efficient manner, thus preserving operational continuity.
